ive_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Married her step-uncle's son","body":"Sarah Batt's stepfather Josiah Torrey was the brother of her husband Micajah Torrey Jr.'s father Micajah Torrey Sr. — Sarah therefore married her step-uncle's son. Her own children were both step-cousins to and children-in-law of the broader Torrey family network. The step-family marriage pattern was common in colonial New England where remarriages frequently rearranged the kinship of small village populations."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Nine documented children with Micajah Torrey Jr.","body":"Sarah and Micajah Torrey Jr. had nine documented children. The marriage produced the largest single Batt-Torrey family cluster of the late-seventeenth and early-eighteenth-century Boston-and-Weymouth Massachusetts area, with the family settling primarily at Weymouth where Sarah lived out her long widowhood-and-old-age decades."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Lived to ninety; gravestone reads eighty-fifth year","body":"Sarah lived to approximately age ninety — born January 18, 1673 in Boston and died May 10, 1763 in Weymouth, a span of ninety years and three months. The Weymouth gravestone reads 'in ye 85th year of her age' — a discrepancy suggesting either an inaccurate stone inscription or a contemporary error in computing her age. The colonial gravestone tradition of counting the running year rather than completed years often produced such variations."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Boston 1673 to Weymouth Massachusetts 1763","body":"Sarah Batt was born January 18, 1673 in Boston Massachusetts, daughter of Paul Batt and Sarah Wilson Torrey. She died May 10, 1763 in Weymouth Massachusetts. Her ninety-year life spanned from the early years of King Philip's War through to the eve of the American Revolution."},{"number":5,"category":"family","header":"Widowed twice, she married a deacon","body":"Three years after Micajah Torrey died, Sarah marrie